const faqs = [{"question": "What counts as premature ejaculation?", "answer": "The International Society for Sexual Medicine defines lifelong PE as ejaculation that always or nearly always occurs within about 1 minute of penetration, from the first sexual experience. Acquired PE involves a clinically significant reduction in latency time, often to about 3 minutes or less. However, the key criterion is that it causes distress. If you and your partner are both satisfied, the timing matters less than the experience."}, {"question": "Can home remedies really help with PE?", "answer": "Some home approaches have genuine evidence behind them. Behavioral techniques (start-stop, squeeze method) and pelvic floor exercises have been studied in clinical trials and shown meaningful improvements. Lifestyle changes like exercise, stress management, and sleep optimization support overall sexual health. However, supplements and herbal remedies have much weaker evidence and should not be relied upon as primary treatments."}, {"question": "How long do behavioral techniques take to work?", "answer": "Most men begin noticing improvements within 2–4 weeks of consistent practice with behavioral techniques like the start-stop method. Significant improvements typically occur over 6–12 weeks. Pelvic floor exercises generally require 8–12 weeks of consistent practice before noticeable results. Consistency is the key factor."}, {"question": "Do numbing sprays and creams work for PE?", "answer": "Yes, topical anesthetics (lidocaine or benzocaine-based sprays and creams) are one of the most effective and well-studied treatments for PE. They work by reducing penile sensitivity, which can extend time to ejaculation. They are available over the counter and have been shown in clinical trials to increase intravaginal ejaculatory latency time (IELT) by 2–3 times or more."}, {"question": "Is premature ejaculation psychological or physical?", "answer": "PE can be both. Some men have heightened penile sensitivity or neurobiological factors (such as serotonin receptor differences) that contribute to rapid ejaculation. Psychological factors, including performance anxiety, stress, relationship issues, and early sexual conditioning, also play significant roles. Many men have a combination of physical and psychological contributors."}];

